== Events == * [[1433]] &ndash; Baverius de Bonittis starts teaching philosophy and logic at the University of Bologna<ref>Kristeller, p. 440</ref> * 1433 &ndash; [[Ambrogio Traversari]] completed his translation of ''[[Lives and Opinions of Eminent Philosophers]]''<ref>{{multiref|Schmitt, p. 70|Lepage, p. 27}}</ref>
== Publications == * [[1433]] &ndash; [[Lorenzo Valla]] publishes his much modified second edition of ''[[De voluptate]]'' (''On Pleasure'') while on sojourn in [[Pavia]]<ref>Lorch, p. 214</ref> * [[1499]] &ndash; [[Niccolò Machiavelli]], ''[[Discorso sopra le cose di Pisa]]'' * [[1500]] &ndash; [[Desiderius Erasmus]], ''[[Adagia|Collectanea Adagiorum]]''
== Births == * [[1433]] &ndash; [[Marsilio Ficino]] (d. 1499).<ref>[http://plato.stanford.edu/entries/ficino/#LifStyPlaAca Marsilio Ficino], entry by [https://johnshopkins.academia.edu/ChristopherCelenza Christopher Celenza] in the Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy</ref> Christian [[Neoplatonist]], head of Florentine Academy and major Renaissance Humanist figure. First translator of Plato's complete extant works into Latin. * 1433 &ndash; [[Nil Sorsky]] (d. 1508), Russian [[Hesychast]]<ref>Laos, p. 158</ref> * c.1467 &ndash; [[Erasmus|Desiderius Erasmus]] (d. 1536).<ref>{{cite journal|last=Vredeveld|first=Harry|year=1993|title=The Ages of Erasmus and the Year of His Birth|journal=Renaissance Quarterly|volume=46|issue=4|pages=754–809|jstor=3039022}}</ref> * 1467 &ndash; [[John Major (philosopher)|John Major (or Mair)]] (d. 1550). Scottish logician<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rep.routledge.com/articles/biographical/major-john-1467-1550/v-1|title=Major, John (1467–1550)|last=Biard|first=Joel|work=Routledge Encyclopedia of Philosophy|accessdate=22 September 2018}}</ref>
== Deaths == * [[1432]] or [[1433]] &ndash; [[Ibn Turkah]] (Sa'in al-Din Turkah Isfahani), an influential Turcoman scholar and [[Sufi philosophy|Sufist philosopher]] at the [[School of Isfahan]], exiled by [[Tamerlane]] until the latter's death. The date of Ibn Turkah's death is uncertain; either 1432 or 1433.<ref>Nasr, p. 209</ref> * [[1499]] &ndash; [[Marsilio Ficino]] (b. 1433). See {{section link||Births}}
