[[File:Duncan, William – The elements of logic, 1811 – BEIC 769468.jpg|thumb|In ''The elements of logic'' (1811), [[William Duncan (philosopher)|William Duncan]] combined a [[John Locke|Lockean]] theory of knowledge with [[Syllogism|syllogistic]] [[logic]].<ref name=CHECP>{{Citation | last=Haakonssen | first=Knud | year=2006 | contribution=Duncan, William | editor-last=Haakonssen | editor-first=Knud | title=The Cambridge History of Eighteenth-Century Philosophy | publisher=Cambridge University Press | volume=2 | pages=1166}}</ref>]]

In [[philosophy]], '''gnosology''' literally means the study of ''[[gnosis]]'', meaning [[knowledge]] or [[esoteric knowledge]]. Gnosology has also been used to render [[Johann Gottlieb Fichte]]'s term for his own version of [[transcendental idealism]], ''[[Foundations of the Science of Knowledge|Wissenschaftslehre]]'', meaning "Doctrine of Knowledge".<ref>Albert Schwegler, [https://books.google.com/books?id=Yio-AAAAYAAJ&q= ''Handbook of the history of philosophy''], Edmondston & Co., 1879, p. 259.</ref>

